<h2 id="onsite-seo" name="onsite-seo">Onsite SEO</h2>
<p>If you're looking to attract more visitors to your site, the most sensible thing to look at first is your onsite SEO (Search Engine Optimisation). Onsite SEO is essentially how well optimised your website content is for your audience (from Google's perspective).</p>

<p><strong>First steps in assessing your SEO are likely to be:</strong></p>
<ul>
	<li>Keyword research (what terms are people using to find organisations such as yours)</li>
	<li>Domain name (if it's a new website and you haven't bought a domain name, you can boost rankings by purchasing a domain name that includes the most important keyword)</li>
	<li>Header tags (H1 - H2), Google likes well organised and semantic content. Correct usage of HTML tags and headings will give you a boost here</li>
	<li>Page Titles - meta title's should be unique to every page, short and include some highly relevant keywords to that page's content</li>
	<li>Meta descriptions - these won't improve your SEO in Google's eyes, but they are what get shown to users in a Google results page, so are highly influential in encouraging a user to select your site to visit over a competitors</li>
	<li>Quality and relevant content - ensure your content is up-to-date, well written and focussed on the visitor's requirements. Don't stuff pages with lots of keywords for the sake of it. Google is cleverer than this and will penalise you.</li>
	<li>Image file names and alt text - rename all your images with a file name that is readable and descriptive. Also use the alt tag field on images to describe the picture</li>
</ul>

<p>All of the above can be accomplished reasonably easily and economically as part of your normal ongoing website managment. Results from this would be reflected in your <em>organic</em> search.</p>

<p>Organic search is highly regarded by search engine users, because it's well known good rankings will only be achieved with time and effort. Good rankings are often directly related to the reputability of the business. There are no real costs other than time of someone to research and analyise your website analytics and update site content accordingly. The drawbacks are that it can take a long time to start seeing results - sometimes 3-6 months, and it is an ongoing job.</p>

