<h3 id="paidsearch" name="paidsearch">Paid Search (AdWords)</h3>

<p>Paid Search (through Google AdWords) can be a quicker route to getting website traffic. It can be expensive: you have to pay for evryone who clicks on one of your adverts and you need to have someone looking at the account regularly to keep on top of its optimisation.</p>

<p>With good managment, an AdWords account can still be a worthwhile investment and give you good ROI - but it should not be considered an <em>alternative</em> to your organic search SEO and should only be run in support of an otherwise well optimised webiste.</p>

<p><strong>Some particular instances of when Paid Search Marketing should be considered:</strong></p>

<ul>
	<li>When SEO hasn't, or can't, kick in</li>
	<li>Time sensitive promotional offers</li>
	<li>To gain a competitive edge</li>
	<li>Brand awareness</li>
</ul>

<h4>How to get good ROI from your AdWords campaign</h4>

<p>While you bid on keywords in Google AdWords, the person paying the most for a given keyword isn't necessarily going to be placed at the top of the page.</p>
<p>Google has a complex algorythm to assess the relevance of a website to each paid-for-phrase. You can significantly reduce costs-per-click and increase click through numbers by following some basic principles.</p>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Well structured campaigns:</strong><br />
	break your AdWord campaigns into small and highly targeted groups. Google typically rewards this type of stucture</li>
	<li><strong>Keyword and Ad text relevancy:</strong><br />
	once you have small and higly targeted groups, you can ensure the Ad Texts and associated keywords are highly relevant and targeted. Avoid broad and generic terms.</li>
	<li><strong>Relevant, optimised landing pages:</strong><br />
	 don't send all your traffic to the home page or top level category page. Take customers to the most specific page on your site. In some situations it is worthwhile creating specific landing pages for campaigns with highly relevant content.</li>
	<li>Solid Ad creative - USPs and a call-to-action: keep refining your Ad Text to maximise click through rates. Even small changes can have major impacts (good and bad) on an adverts performance</li>
	<li><strong>Ad and Landing page testing:</strong><br />
	try multiple variations on every advert and variations on your landing pages. Constantly monitor and refine based on traffic numbers, cost and conversion rates</li>
	<li><strong>Monitor your Quality score</strong><br />
	Google will give all campaigns a quality score based on how relevant they think your campaigns are to the web pages you're directing traffic to. Refine your Ads and the landing pages to increase your quality score. This will lower your cost per click.</li>
	<li><strong>Link AdWords with Analytics</strong><br />
	 to allow you to monitor the click through rate, bounce rates and conversion rates closely</li> 
	</ul>
	
<p>If you want to set start using Google AdWords or learn how to make an existing campaign run better <a href="http://taylormade.training/adwords-training" title="Google AdWords Training">look at our Google AdWords training courses</a>.</p>

