<h3 id="social-media" name="social-media">Social Media and Blogging</h3>

<p>The proliferation of Social Media and blogging has been fast and profound over the last few years. It can be intimidating and time consuming to manage yet another, highly public, online marketing stream. But it brings a wide set of benefits for your business if managed correctly.</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Engaging with customers:</strong><br />
	don't just broadcast to followers on Facebook or Twitter, but engage in two-way conversations</li>
	<li><strong>Creating buzz:</strong><br />
	it's so easy to share content on Social Media channels, it's a quick and easy way to get new content out to a wide audience</li>
	<li><strong>Widening the net:</strong><br />
	fans of Social Media love to share content with their followers. By regularly engaging with your customers online there's greater chance of your content being shared and found by potential new customers</li>
	<li><strong>Quality inbound links:</strong><br />
	Google his significance to the number of links back to your website. Activity on Social Media can create a number of inbound links back to you, for an SEO boost</li>
	<li><strong>Higher position in SERPs:</strong><br />
	results in Social Media channels often is ranked higher that content from regular websites. By engaging in Social Media channels you have greater likelihood of being found in rankings.</li>
</ul>

<h4>How to go about it</h4>
<p><strong>You need to have a strategy:</strong></p>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Commit:</strong><br /> Social Media is a 24/7 activity. You don't need to have someone monitoring it around the clock - but it does need regular checks and updates throught the day. It can't be left to a Friday afternoon or just when someone has a spare 5 minutes.</li>
	<li><strong>Focus:</strong> <br />there are many Social Media channels. The more you can be active on the better, but only if you can keep up with the demands. Typically, focus on the most popular and relevant to your audience. Typically this is Facebook, Twitter, Google+, LinkedIn and a blog. If you are short on resources, it might be better to only use one or two of these</li>
	<li><strong>Plan:</strong><br /> who will be managing the accounts, agree a tone of voice, topics, offers, best practice for complaints</li>
</ul>
