<h3 id="email" name="email">Email Marketing</h3>

<p>People can be wary of marketing emails and you must be very careful of not abusing your list with needless emails. But a well run email campaign can still be a valuable exercise as part of your digital marketing campaign.</p>

<p>It is better to build your own list rather than buying in names. You will likely see a far greater return on ROI only sending to people who have <em>actively opted in</em> to receiving your email.</p>

<p>Don't trick people into giving their email address and don't add them to your list without telling them. But do encourage people to sign up with a prominent newsletter signup form on your website. This form can also be included in your Facebook page, blog pages or paid search ads. You can further incentivise people to signup through use of competitions and promotions. Offline data collection might also be an option at events or exhibitions. Just be clear to people what you will be doing with their email, and allow them to opt out.</p>

<h4>Then what?</h4>

<p>You've got a list of customers who want to stay in touch with you ...</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Do stay in touch.</strong><br /> Make sure you are sending regular emails, with quality content</li>
	<li><strong>Stick to a schedule.</strong><br /> Weekly or monthly newsletters breeds familiarity, trust, reputability and value. Users are more likely to opt out of newsletters that are erratic as they won't build a rapport with you.</li>
	<li><strong>Keep it interesting and relevant:</strong><br /> make some effort in your newsletters. Give your customers something they wouldn't get elsewhere. This can be a mix of compelling information, competitions or promotions</li>
	<li>Allow customers to share the content, include social media links</li>
	<li><strong>Let customers opt out.</strong><br /> Just because someone doesn't want your newsletter any more doesn't mean they don't want to use your business again. But if you make it difficult to opt out of your emails, they might get a negative view of you</li>
</ul>
